==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*skizo''.  Cognate with Old High German [[scira|scīra]].

====Pronunciation====
[[IPA]]: /ʃɪr/

====Noun====
'''scir''' 
# a [[shire]], consisting of a number of [[hundred]]s or [[wapentake]]s, ruled jointly by an [[alderman]] and a [[sheriff]]

===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*skeira-''.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[skire]], Old Saxon [[skir|skīr]] (Dutch [[schier]] ‘white, grey’, German [[schier]] ‘pure’), Old Norse [[skirr|skírr]] (Swedish [[skir]]), Gothic [[𐍃𐌺𐌴𐌹𐍂𐍃]].  Related to [[scinan]].

====Pronunciation====
[[IPA]]: /ʃi:r/

====Adjective====
'''scīr'''
# [[bright]], [[shining]]
# [[clear]], [[pure]]

